repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
* constant C arrays: `static const` C arrays in place
* module global: static C arrays in the module init function
* inside generators: non-const arrays stored in the generator closure
* otherwise: non-const local temp array variables on the stack

The constant case specifically applies to for-loop iteration over strings etc. It avoids the need to store them away in generator closures and generally wasting runtime work for them.

Factors a dedicated `CArrayNode` out of the `ListNode` for the "list as C array" case, to avoid complicating `ListNode` for this. I kept `ListNode` as a base class mostly just in case we need some of its functionality later on, but I'm not aware of anything specific that is needed. It could probably just be a `SequenceNode`. We should be looking at `is_sequence_constructor` rather than specific `ListNode` / `TupleNode` classes wherever it's needed.

Also enables coercion from a Unicode string literal to an integer C array of character values (not just `Py_UCS4[]` but also e.g. `short[]` for more compact storage of BMP Unicode characters). I think that's a reasonable thing to have. It doesn't do any compile time value checking, but the C compiler would probably warn.

It'd be a somewhat large change for 3.2.x but maybe not too risky. Thus also the `ListNode` base class, to reduce the risk of unanticipated changes.

Closes https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/7323

I don't think it does any harm, but all the examples I can find are allocated in a local scope (either the module-init function, or in an individual function, or in the closure struct) so the names don't need to be globally unique.

Although maybe it makes them easier to reason about if they are.

comment_data.body:
Why can't you re-use it?

I agree with the "you must allocate it on the stack" (I think there is a nicer way to do it in C), but you are just manually filling in the contents here and you can do that multiple times.

If I set `reusable=True` then it appears to work in all your tests so if you've found a corner case that I've missed (quite likely!) then it isn't explicitly tested.

commit.message:
Prevent an invalid assignment from a C string array.
Previously, "cdef char[3] name = 'ABC'" tried to cast the C string constant to a C array type and tried to copy that into the stack array.
Add tests for https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/7323
Add tests for string iteration in generator expressions.
Use a "static const" C array for constant array literals to avoid having them turn up in closure temps etc.
Prevent casting a literal const C array to non-const when memcpy()ing it.

Revert "Prevent casting a literal const C array to non-const when memcpy()ing it."

It was not strictly related to this PR.
This reverts commit dd7b8302b229f4a5b9cfc18f48d0f782400b7f20.
Add missing newline at end of test file.
Allocate C arrays in generators in their closure and never consider C arrays temp, to make using code adapt accordingly.
Fix re-coercion of CArrayNode after initial creation.
Use "const itemtype" instead of "const array" for constant literal C arrays.
Use "const itemtype" instead of "const array" also for the C array iteration.
Fix accidentally duplicated 'const'.
Add generated test suite for carray iteration.
Add generated test suite for carray iteration.
Allow assignments and iteration of unicode and bytes string literals as integer arrays.
Fix string to char* coercion by reordering conditions.
Include assignment from array to pointer.
Fix UnicodeNode instantiation.
Use predefined name.
Remove some redundant tests.
Prevent allocating "static const" arrays for dynamic items.

Add test for declaring const C arrays.

These do not currently generate the expected code because they assign to the array via "memcpy()" only after creating it. However, the declaration as "const array" rather than "const itemtype" arrays made this work and we should keep it working somehow.
Store dynamically created C arrays as non-const arrays in closure and stack.
Fix unique test function naming and 'arg' usage.
Reduce number of test cases.
Fix error reporting when coercing a Unicode string literal to an incompatible char/void pointer.
Remove invalid tests.
Fix test decorators and counters.
Improve comment.
Normalise spacing between test functions.
Update test tags.

Fix 0-terminated char* iteration by preventing C array iteration in this case and apply the iterable optimisations to both the iterable and its potentially unpacked originally typed form to avoid missing an opportunity.
Move trial optimisations into separate methods to fix a name mixup and make the code generally clearer.
Exclude invalid tests: cannot currently assign to 'const' array variables because the assignment happens after the declaration.
Remove now-invalid test file.
Merge branch 'master' into gh7323_gen_carray_static
